'''Anders Beer''' (8 July 1875 – 1957) was a Norwegian businessperson.
He was born in [[Oslo|Kristiania]]. He spent his career as chief executive of the [[stonemasonry]] company N. S. Beer & Co,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kjent forretningsmann fyller 80 år|author=|date=8 July 1955|work=[[Aftenposten Aften]]|page=2}}</ref> founded by his father Nicolai Sivert Beer in 1879. The company was a major exporter of pavement stones globally. It was changed into the public company Beer Sten in 1989. The company was passed down to the next generation (Gerhard Beer), then the next after that (Anders Beer, Jr.).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beersten.no/beersten%20historie.htm|title=Vår historie|publisher=Beer Sten|language=Norwegian|accessdate=9 March 2012}}</ref>
He was also a supervisory council of [[Forsikringsselskapet Viking]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vikings generalforsamling|work=[[Aftenposten]]|language=Norwegian|date=4 April 1935|page=6}}</ref> He was a member of the gentlemen's skiing club [[SK Fram (Oslo)|SK Fram]] since 1906.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Qvale, Fredrik|editor-link=Fredrik Qvale|year=1989|title=Skiklubben Fram 100 år|language=Norwegian|pages=9–11}}</ref> He died in 1957 and was buried in [[Ullern]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disnorge.no/gravminner/index.php?language=engelsk|title=Cemeteries in Norway|publisher=DIS-Norge|accessdate=9 March 2012}}</ref>
