The '''Lovelace Tavern''' was a bar located in what is now the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. Owned by the then-[[List of colonial governors of New York|governor of New York colony]], [[Francis Lovelace|Colonel Francis Lovelace]], it was in business from 1670 until 1706.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theboweryboys.blogspot.com/2010/10/lovelace-tavern-early-new-york-history.html|title=Lovelace's Tavern: Early New York History, Under Foot|website=The Bowery Boys: New York History|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref><ref name="Jameson1997">{{cite book||last1=Baugher |first1=Sherene |last2=Wall |first2=Diana Dizerega |editor-last=Jameson |editor-first=John H., Jr. |title=Presenting Archaeology to the Public: Digging for Truths|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NklAkoN2-wcC&pg=PA119|date=1997|location=Walnut Creek, CA|publisher=AltaMira Press|isbn=978-0-7619-8909-7|pages=119–121|chapter=Ancient and Modern United}}</ref> The building's remains were discovered in 1979, when construction for present-day [[85 Broad Street|85]] [[Broad Street (Manhattan)|Broad Street]] was taking place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forgotten-ny.com/2004/07/forgotten-tour-17-lower-manhattan/|title=Forgotten Tour 17, Lower Manhattan|website=Forgotten New York|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref><ref name="NeviusNevius2009">{{cite book|author1=Michelle Nevius|author2=James Nevius|title=Inside the Apple: A Streetwise History of New York City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3qRsoicp48C&pg=PT38|date=2009|location=New York|publisher=Free Press|isbn=978-1-4165-9393-5|page=38}}</ref> The building burned down in 1706, but the original foundation walls can be seen today through glass set into the sidewalk.
